.alert.alert-light.border.mb-0
  %h3.fw-semibold.mb-2 Goal of this page
  %p.mb-3
    Choose existing goals to become
    %strong parents
    of
    %strong= @goal.title
    so this goal sits in the right place in the goal hierarchy.

  %h3.fw-semibold.mb-2 Context
  %p.mb-3
    Parent links mean “pursuing this goal is in service of those parents.” Company, department, and team goals form the shared org graph; teammate goals stay personal unless they are visible company-wide or you created them for that owner.

  %h3.fw-semibold.mb-2 Specifics of this page
  %h5.fw-semibold.mb-2 Which goals appear
  %ul.mb-3
    %li Incomplete goals only (draft or started)—not completed or archived.
    %li
      If this goal is
      %strong company-owned,
      parents can only be other
      %strong company-owned
      goals visible to everyone in the company.
    %li
      If this goal is
      %strong department-
      or
      %strong team-owned,
      parents can be company, department, or team goals visible to everyone in the company.
    %li
      If this goal is
      %strong teammate-owned,
      parents are that owner’s goals you created or that are visible to everyone in the company, plus company/department/team goals visible to everyone in the company.

  %h5.fw-semibold.mb-2 Hierarchy rule (easy to forget)
  %p.mb-3
    Company, department, and team goals
    %strong cannot
    have a teammate-owned goal as a parent. Teammate goals can link
    %em up
    into the org graph; the org graph does not hang under a personal goal.

  %h5.fw-semibold.mb-2 Example
  .border.rounded.p-3.bg-white.mb-0
    %p.small.mb-1
      Department goal
      %strong Ship Q3 launch
      → selectable parents include company-visible company/dept/team goals such as
      %em Grow revenue
      or
      %em Product roadmap.
    %p.small.text-muted.mb-0
      A private teammate goal like
      %em Finish my certification
      will not appear for that department child.
